  "title": "Purpose, Mastery, Autonomy",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "194af06d4831bcd0",
      "text": "British Columbia is a high performing system. One of the features of this system is the existence of a voluntary network of educators with a clear purpose. The networks use a 'spiral of inquiry' in a drive to understand an identified issue and improve learning and life outcomes for their students. It is an iterative  process of checking, scanning, focusing, developing a hunch, learning and taking action."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c3358dd647b132e1",
      "text": "What this approach recognises is that when you offer smart people, doing complex work like teaching, a clear purpose and the opportunity to get on with the job, they do so in powerful ways. Daniel Pink's book, Drive, explains why. What is absent in this approach is coercion, bureaucratic restrictions and undue system accountabilities and monitoring measures."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "08abeff6874ee1b0",
      "text": "In the majority of Western systems the drive for improvement comes from focusing on standardised test scores, comparative performance data, discussion of teacher performance and teaching quality, league tables and in some performance pay. In many systems, the industrial mindset is when there is evidence a particular strategy can produce academic results, that [[Shiny Thing]] it is imposed from above. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6f9351a32b26fb5e",
      "text": "What I learned from NOII is what we need is not large educational bureaucracies, but agile structures in schools where high levels of safety are present, iterative cycles of learning benefit all and accountability flows from purpose, rather than being imposed. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "15fc0011e2a6cf47",
      "text": "This can be achieved with the right conditions within the school and better recognition that [[Meso Level Activity]] is key to system growth. This has been the contribution of the voluntary networks in British Columbia."
    },
